          </p>

          <ol>
            <li><strong>Obtain the original document</strong> from your home country (birth certificate, marriage certificate, degree, police clearance)</li>
            <li><strong>Home country authentication.</strong> For <a href="/resources/attestation-guide/">Hague Convention member countries</a> (India, UK, USA, Philippines, Bangladesh, Canada): notarization followed by apostille. For non-Hague countries (Pakistan, Egypt): notarization, home country MOFA, then UAE Embassy in your home country.</li>
            <li><strong>UAE MOFA attestation.</strong> AED 150 per document, 1-3 working days, processed through the eDAS 2.0 system.</li>
            <li><strong>Arabic translation by MOJ-certified translator.</strong> This step must come after attestation. The translation needs to capture the attestation stamps and stickers on the document.</li>
            <li><strong>Typing center data entry.</strong> The typing center uploads your documents into the GDRFA system.</li>
            <li><strong>GDRFA review and decision.</strong> Electronic review. Entry permit arrives via email or SMS if approved.</li>
          </ol>

          <div class="callout-block warning">
            <strong>Critical sequencing rule:</strong> Translation must come AFTER attestation. If you translate first and then get the document attested, the translation will not show the attestation markings. GDRFA expects translated attestation stamps. You will need a new translation, which means paying twice.
          </div>

          <p>
            The GDRFA portal uses a general document upload system that accepts up to 10 documents per application. Documents are not uploaded to labeled fields (no separate "birth certificate" slot). This means the typing center's accuracy in organizing and labeling your documents matters.
          </p>
        </section>

