            This is especially common with <a href="/blog/marriage-certificate-translation-dubai/">marriage certificates</a> and <a href="/blog/birth-certificate-translation-uae-visa/">birth certificates</a>. If your name is transliterated differently on your passport versus your supporting documents, GDRFA may flag the discrepancy.
          </p>

          <p>
            Examples that cause problems:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>Mohammed vs. Muhammad vs. Mohamed</li>
            <li>Surname differences between maiden name on birth certificate and married name on passport</li>
            <li>Father's name transliterated differently across documents</li>
            <li>Middle names present on one document but absent on another</li>
          </ul>

          <p>
            The MOJ-certified translator can add a clarifying note to the translation when name variations exist. This is not a guarantee of acceptance, but it addresses the discrepancy proactively.
          </p>

          <h3>4. Expired or Invalid Documents</h3>

